                <fr:anchor>7324</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00N3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00N3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Closure of injections under identity and composition">Closure of <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injections</fr:link> under <fr:link href="jms-00II.xml" title="The identity relation" addr="jms-00II" type="local">identity</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00IN.xml" title="Relational composite" addr="jms-00IN" type="local">composition</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The <fr:link href="jms-00KI.xml" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition" addr="jms-00KI" type="local">identity function</fr:link> is an <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link> and the <fr:link href="jms-00IN.xml" title="Relational composite" addr="jms-00IN" type="local">composition</fr:link> of <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injections</fr:link> yields a <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7323</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6085</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6085.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>The <fr:link href="jms-00KI.xml" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition" addr="jms-00KI" type="local">identity function</fr:link> is clearly <fr:link href="jms-00KI.xml" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition" addr="jms-00KI" type="local">injective</fr:link>, as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\rightarrowtail  B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\colon  B\rightarrowtail  C]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link href="jms-00M0.xml" title="The axiom of infinity" addr="jms-00M0" type="local">injections</fr:link>. To show that the <fr:link href="jms-00KI.xml" title="Closure of functions under identity and composition" addr="jms-00KI" type="local">composite function</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\circ  f\colon  A\to  C]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injective</fr:link>, we fix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0,a_1\in  A]]></fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g{\mathopen {}\left (f{\mathopen {}\left (a_0\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}} = g{\mathopen {}\left (f{\mathopen {}\left (a_1\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex>. Because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injective</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a_0\right )\mathclose {}}=f{\mathopen {}\left (a_1\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; therefore, because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injective</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_0=a_1]]></fr:tex> as desired.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Now that we have enough definitions in hand to see it, the import of <fr:link href="jms-00M7.xml" title="Logical characterisation of bijections" addr="jms-00M7" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00M7" /></fr:link> is then to state that a <fr:link href="jms-00KF.xml" title="Function" addr="jms-00KF" type="local">function</fr:link> is <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijective</fr:link> if and only if it is both <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injective</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00M8.xml" title="Surjection" addr="jms-00M8" type="local">surjective</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>30</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7326</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-00N4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-00N4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Counting injections between finite sets">Counting <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injections</fr:link> between <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite sets</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:link href="jms-00LX.xml" title="Finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local">finite sets</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, we can describe number of <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injections</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> as follows:</fr:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \mathord {\#}{\mathrm {Inj}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}} =
 \begin {cases}
  {\mathord {\#}{B}\choose \mathord {\#}{A}}\cdot  {\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}\right )\mathclose {}}! &\text {when } \mathord {\#}{A}\leq  \mathord {\#}{B}
  \\
  0 &\text {otherwise}
 \end {cases}
]]></fr:tex>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>30</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7325</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6086</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6086.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We will argue from a combinatoric perspective.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>An <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> associates no more than one <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> to the same <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>as each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  U]]></fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that is in <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link href="jms-00KR.xml" title="Bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{B}\choose  \mathord {\#}{A}]]></fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:link href="jms-00KT.xml" title="Counting bijections between finite sets" addr="jms-00KT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KT" /></fr:link> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}!\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
